{
  "texts": [
    "For example, the UTRefactor framework [48] successfully removed 89% of test smells by combining a Domain-Specific Language (DSL) with Chain-of-Thought (CoT) prompting, offering a promising direction for improving the engineering quality of generated tests.",
    "These maintainability issues stem primarily from the probabilistic nature of LLMs, which tends to favor conciseness and token efficiency over strict adherence to software engineering best practices; for example, preferring a literal value like 5 over a named constant.",
    "Furthermore, this behavior is reinforced by the training data, where the prevalence of code smells in open-source projects leads models to mimic and amplify suboptimal human coding habits [104].",
    "To address this problem, frameworks like ASTER explicitly target the generation of natural and readable tests, with user studies confirming that their generated tests are even more understandable than some human-written ones, receiving high approval from developers [108].6.1.2 Limitations of Models.",
    "These quality issues stem from the architectural constraints of the models."
  ]
}